PMID:15339905 RAS proteins are members of the GTPase family which are active in the GTP bound form and inactive in the GDP-bound form. Rapid glucose enhancement of RAS2 is dependent upon CDC25 and SDC25 and is negatively impacted by the IRA proteins. CDC25 plays a more prominent role than SDC25 PMID:3545497 Furthermore, mutationally activated alleles of CDC25 are capable of inducing a set of phenotypes similar to those observed in strains containing a genetically activated RAS/adenylate cyclase pathway, suggesting that CDC25 encodes a regulatory protein. We propose that CDC25 regulates adenylate cyclase by regulating the guanine nucleotide bound to RAS proteins. PMID:2188363 Partially purified preparations of the carboxy-terminal domain of the SCD25 gene product enhanced the exchange rate of guanosine diphosphate (GDP) to guanosine triphosphate (GTP) of pure RAS2 protein by stimulating the release of GDP. PMID:2017169 In this report, we provide an identification of Cdc25p, the product of the CDC25 gene, and evidence that it promotes exchange of guanine nucleotides bound to Ras in vitro.

PMID:15282298 In the presence of glucose, RIM11 is phosphorylated at S5, S8 and S12 by PKA thus making it inactive. In glucose limitation, RIM11 is active and catalyses phosphorylation of IME1 and subsequent entry into meiosis and formation of spores.

PMID:15282298 The budding yeast homolog Rim11 is essential for the exit of diploid cells from the cell cycle and for entry into the meiotic developmental pathway IME1 is silent when glucose is present since its activator RIM11 is inactive. As soon as glucose limitation occurs, RIM11 gets active and the meiotic signal passes onto IME1 that activates all the meiosis specific genes. Rim11 and Ime1 associate in the presence of glucose (40), nevertheless, phosphorylation of Ime1 by Rim11 depends on glucose depletion. This fact suggests either that glucose inhibits the kinase activity of Rim11 or that Ime1 is not accessible to phosphorylation in the presence of glucose. Phosphorylation of IME1 by RIM11 is done on Tyr-359 and Ser-302 and/or Ser-306. We have shown that phosphorylation on TYR 359 is essential for sporulation.
